{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"807399f5-e069-4ad6-a387-c3ec03933c37","content":"Use `dotnet watch test` — it re-runs tests automatically whenever you save a file:\n\n```bash\ndotnet watch test --filter \"RemoveStock_ExceedsAvailable_ThrowsException\"\n```\n\nThe `--filter` flag limits it to just the failing test for faster feedback.\n\n**The bug:** `RemoveStock` subtracts without checking if there's enough stock. It should throw when `quantity > available`. Fix line 37:\n\n```csharp\npublic void RemoveStock(string sku, int quantity)\n{\n    var current = _stock.GetValueOrDefault(sku);\n    if (quantity > current)\n        throw new InvalidOperationException($\"Cannot remove {quantity}, only {current} available.\");\n    _stock[sku] = current - quantity;\n}\n```\n\nWith `dotnet watch` running, just save the file and the test will re-run automatically. Want me to apply the fix?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"906c74a8-3ace-4e86-a32b-ed53b3959200","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to set up hot reload for this test project. With .NET and Microsoft.Testing.Platform, they can use `dotnet test --hotreload` or `dotnet watch test`. Let me check what's available.\n\nSince this is using `Microsoft.Testing.Platform` (from global.json) and .NET 10, they can use `dotnet test --hotreload` which is a newer feature. But actually, the classic approach is `dotnet watch test`.\n\nLet me just explain how to use `dotnet watch test` for hot reload, which will re-run tests whenever files change.\n\nActually, with .NET 10 and Microsoft.Testing.Platform, there might be `dotnet test --hotreload` support. \n\nI'll go with `dotnet watch test` since it's the reliable, well-established way to handle this, and I can also help them spot and fix the bug in their code.","outputTokens":429,"requestId":"BD1D:134464:1B6D91E:1EF0CF2:6A07BF67"},"id":"1a496e4b-f8c9-40ae-9a36-59a2f935dbca","timestamp":"2026-05-16T00:50:58.628Z","parentId":"400ec39c-10cb-46d3-8af8-14